Freedropping, which sees sees enthusiasts jumping from extreme heights onto large safety airbags performing twists, flips and turns as they drop, has exploded in popularity over the past few years.

Mr Roe said: 'I simply wanted to try something new. I wanted to test my skills where they had never been tested before.'

Mr Roe's jump - his latest in a long line of never before performed tricks - is just one pulled by the freedrop acrobat during the adrenaline-fuelled session.

