He added: 'I have to make sure I land perfectly in the centre of my back each time I jump. I am falling too fast for another landing to be safe.

'I am a trained professional so I can stay safe even at extreme heights.'

Mr Roe, who trained as an Olympic level trampolinist, said he has been able to translate those traditional skills onto a bigger stage.

Each jump poses a number of challenges.

Freedropping is the latest extreme sport craze coming in the wake of bungee jumping, where people jump from high bridges attached to an elasticated cord and base-jumping where people parachute jump from tall buildings or cliffs.

